description: From the Spanish mondongo (“tripe, entrails”), perhaps via its English etymon mondongo.

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Offal; waste animal product; organic matter unfit for consumption.
examples: Claret is the universal medicine here, and mundungus port the bane and stupefaction of all society.

entries.meaning: (archaic) Poor-quality tobacco with a foul, rancid, or putrid smell.
examples: Whom he brings in among usAnd bribes with mundungus;
